</article><article class="clearfix full-article has-hero-image  time_article " id="article-3592071" data-article="3592071" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Article">
  <header class="article-header">
    
    <section class="tags ">
  		  <a class="brand-tag brand-time-tag" href="http://time.com/" data-bypass="true">TIME</a>


            <a class="section-tag" itemprop="articleSection" href="http://time.com/history/" data-event="section-history">History</a>

            <a class="topic-tag" itemprop="articleSection" href="http://time.com/tag/technology/" data-event="tag-technology" data-bypass="true">technology</a>

      </section>
    <h2 class="article-title" itemprop="headline">It Took Microsoft 3 Tries Before Windows Was Successful</h2>
  <div class="article-sub-headline">
    <div class="article-meta">

        <ul class="article-authors">
            <li class="article-author ">
              <span class="byline"><a itemprop="author" href="http://time.com/author/alex-fitzpatrick/">Alex Fitzpatrick</a></span>
              <a class="author-twitter" target="_blank" href="https://twitter.com/alexjamesfitz">@alexjamesfitz</a>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <time class="publish-date" itemprop="datePublished" datetime="2014-11-20 07:00:20" pubdate>Nov. 20, 2014</time>
      
    </div>
    <div class="social-links">
      <a class="expand-share" href="javascript:void 0;" data-event="exp-micro" title="Click to view article share options">SHARE</a>
    <span class="social-links-tooltip">
    	<a class="time-icons time-icons-mail social-link-mail" href="mailto:?subject=It%20Took%20Microsoft%203%20Tries%20Before%20Windows%20Was%20Successful%20%7C%20TIME&body=It%20Took%20Microsoft%203%20Tries%20Before%20Windows%20Was%20Successful%0A%0AWindows%201.0%20wasn%27t%20exactly%20a%20huge%20win%20%E2%80%94%20even%20with%20Microsoft%20Paint%20helping%20out%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3592071%2Fwindows-1-history%2F" data-event="email" title="Click to Email this article"></a>
    	<a class="time-icons time-icons-fb social-link-fb popup" href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3592071%2Fwindows-1-history%2F" data-event="fb-share" title="Click to post this article to Facebook"></a>
    	<a class="time-icons time-icons-tw social-link-tw popup" href="#" data-href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwp.me%2Fp5HMd-f4sD&text=Happy%20birthday%20to%20Windows%201.0&via=TIMEHistory" data-event="tweet" title="Click to Tweet this article"></a>
    	<a class="time-icons time-icons-gplus social-link-gplus popup" href="https://plus.google.com/share?url=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3592071%2Fwindows-1-history%2F" data-event="google+" title="Click to post this article to Google+"></a>
    	<a class="time-icons time-icons-linkedin social-link-linkedin popup" href="http://www.linkedin.com/shareArticle?mini=true&url=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3592071%2Fwindows-1-history%2F&title=It+Took+Microsoft+3+Tries+Before+Windows+Was+Successful" data-event="linkedin" title="Click to post this article to LinkedIn"></a>
    	
    </span>    </div>
  </div>  </header>  <section class="article-body" itemprop="articleBody">
    
    <figure class="wide">
      <img src="http://timedotcom.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/windows-microsoft-1.jpg?w=280" itemprop="image" alt="Microsoft Windows 1.0" srcset="http://timedotcom.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/windows-microsoft-1.jpg?w=1680 800w, http://timedotcom.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/windows-microsoft-1.jpg?w=1680 800w 2x"/>
      <figcaption class="image-caption">
        <span class="caption">Microsoft Windows 1.0</span>
        <span class="credit">AP</span>
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
	<h2 class="article-excerpt" itemprop="alternativeHeadline">Windows 1.0 wasn't exactly a huge win â€” even with Microsoft Paint helping out</h2>
    <aside class="right-rail-module rr-related" data-name="rr-related"><div class="read-more-inline related"><a href="http://time.com/3560908/microsoft-office-word-excel-free-app/" class="read-more-article" format-article data-event="rr-related"><img src="http://timedotcom.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/screen568x568-12.jpeg?w=320" alt="" title="Office for iPhone"><h6 class="read-more-list-h">More</h6><h3 class="read-more-inline-title">Microsoft Office Is Now Free for iPhones, iPads and Android</h3></a><a href="http://time.com/3553242/microsoft-monopoly/" class="read-more-article" format-article data-event="rr-related"><h3 class="read-more-inline-title">A Judge Ordered Microsoft to Split. Here&#8217;s Why It&#8217;s Still a Single Company</h3></a></div></aside><p>The first version of Microsoft Windows will be knocking on the door of its third decade Thursday when it turns the ripe old age of 29 &mdash; well past retirement in software years, given that Microsoft officially put it out to pasture in December of 2001. Still, looking back at Windows 1.0 offers exactly what its name implies: A window into how things used to be, and, in a way, how little has changed.</p>
<aside class="right-rail-module rr-partner" data-name="rr-partner"><div class="read-more-list"><h6 class="read-more-list-h">More</h6><a href="http://time.com/3598431/uzbekistan-kazakstan-online-privacy-verint/" class="read-more-list-article" data-event="rr-more">How US Companies Help Central Asian Autocrats Eavesdrop</a><a href="http://time.com/3594004/worlds-tallest-roller-coaster-skyplex-orlando-skyscraper-us-thrill-rides/" class="read-more-list-article" data-event="rr-more">See How Terrifying the Worldâ€™s Tallest Roller Coaster Is Going to Be</a><a href="http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/michael-brown-shooting/pair-suspected-trying-acquire-bombs-ferguson-protests-n254021?cid=par-time_20141122" class="read-more-partner-article" data-event="rr-partner" target="_blank">Feds Suspect Pair Sought Bombs for Ferguson Protests <span>NBC News</span></a><a href="http://www.nbcnews.com/news/crime-courts/ohio-men-wrongly-convicted-murder-after-39-years-released-n253356?cid=par-time_20141122" class="read-more-partner-article" data-event="rr-partner" target="_blank">Two Ohio Men Wrongly Convicted of Murder Walk Free <span>NBC News</span></a><a href="http://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/fsu-shooter-myron-may-left-message-i-do-not-want-n253436?cid=par-time_20141122" class="read-more-partner-article" data-event="rr-partner" target="_blank">FSU Shooter Left Message: 'I Do Not Want to Die in Vain' <span>NBC News</span></a></div></aside><p>First announced in 1983, Microsoft Windows 1.0 wouldn&#8217;t make it to the consumer market for another two years &mdash; making it one of the first pieces of software to be dismissed as &#8220;vaporware,&#8221; a term actually coined by a Microsoft engineer a year before the Windows announcement, as a disparaging title bestowed upon a product that&#8217;s announced but never sees the light of day.</p>
<p>Windows 1.0&#8242;s big selling point was its Graphical User Interface (GUI), intended to replace MS-DOS-style command prompts (C:/DOS/RUN) with a computing style that looked much more like the multitasking, mouse-click-based computing most of us use today. It also came with software intended to show off its new graphical computing environment with what we&#8217;d now call &#8220;apps&#8221; like &#8220;Calendar,&#8221; &#8220;Clock,&#8221; and yes, of course, &#8220;Paint.&#8221;</p>
<p>Windows wasn&#8217;t the first operating system with a GUI as its primary feature. Microsoft rival Apple, for example, beat Windows to that punch by about a year when its Macintosh hit the market in 1984, and other &#8220;desktop&#8221;-style graphical interfaces were floating around before that. (Late Apple CEO Steve Jobs is said to have gotten a nudge towards the Apple desktop interface after visiting a Xerox facility in 1979.) But Windows 1.0 was marketed as an upgrade for people already running MS-DOS &mdash; and, in fact, it ran on top of MS-DOS, so anybody who wanted Windows had to have MS-DOS installed first.</p><div class="content-ad" id="content-ad-3592071"></div>
<p>So did Windows 1.0 fly off the shelves? Not exactly. Early reviews panned the product for running far too slowly &mdash; not the last time the tech press has made that particular critique. The New York <em>Times</em> <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/1986/02/25/science/personal-computers-windows-are-open-at-last.html" target="_blank">wrote</a> that &#8220;running Windows on a PC with 512K of memory is akin to pouring molasses in the Arctic.&#8221; Many reviews said the speed slowdown only got worse when users ran more than one application at a time &mdash; an ability that had been intended as a primary draw. And that weird <em>mouse </em>thing Microsoft insisted Windows users embrace? Lots of people hated it.</p>
<p>Despite those early hiccups, Microsoft didn&#8217;t just give up and close Windows &mdash; a smart move, given that computers running Windows operating systems now make up about 90% of the market. But not even Windows 2.0, released in 1987, set Windows on its path to world dominance. That spark didn&#8217;t come until Windows 3.0, released in 1990 to critical acclaim and widespread adoption, thanks to a redesigned interface and speed improvements. <a href="http://time.com/vault/issue/1990-06-04/page/79/" target="_blank">As TIME put it in the June 4 issue of that year</a>, &#8220;Microsoft seems to have got it right this time.&#8221;</p><aside class="right-rail-module rr-ad" data-name="rr-ad"><div class="right-rail-ad" id="right-rail-ad-3592071"></div></aside><aside class="right-rail-module rr-share" data-name="rr-share"><span class="social-links">
    <a class="time-icons time-icons-mail social-link-mail" href="mailto:?subject=It%20Took%20Microsoft%203%20Tries%20Before%20Windows%20Was%20Successful%20%7C%20TIME&body=It%20Took%20Microsoft%203%20Tries%20Before%20Windows%20Was%20Successful%0A%0AWindows%201.0%20wasn%27t%20exactly%20a%20huge%20win%20%E2%80%94%20even%20with%20Microsoft%20Paint%20helping%20out%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3592071%2Fwindows-1-history%2F" data-event="email" title="Click to Email this article"></a>
    <a class="time-icons time-icons-fb social-link-fb popup" href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3592071%2Fwindows-1-history%2F" data-event="fb-share" title="Click to post this article to Facebook"></a>
    <a class="time-icons time-icons-tw social-link-tw popup" href="#" data-href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwp.me%2Fp5HMd-f4sD&text=Happy%20birthday%20to%20Windows%201.0&via=TIMEHistory" data-event="tweet" title="Click to Tweet this article"></a>
    <a class="time-icons time-icons-linkedin social-link-linkedin popup" href="http://www.linkedin.com/shareArticle?mini=true&url=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3592071%2Fwindows-1-history%2F&title=It+Took+Microsoft+3+Tries+Before+Windows+Was+Successful" data-event="linkedin" title="Click to post this article to LinkedIn"></a>
    <a href="#" class="time-icons time-icons-comment toggle-comments" data-lf-site-id="314099" data-lf-article-id="3592071" data-url="http://time.com/3592071/windows-1-history/" data-title="It Took Microsoft 3 Tries Before Windows Was Successful" title="Click to view and post comments" data-event="comment-click">0</a>
</span>
</aside>
  </section>
